WEBVTT

00:02.127 --> 00:04.129
- The actor who played Brazzos

00:04.129 --> 00:06.215
has his own podcast now.
JIMMY FALLON: What?

00:06.215 --> 00:08.717
- My name is in Fallon's mouth! Wow!

00:08.717 --> 00:10.010
You've got more coming, right?

00:10.010 --> 00:12.638
MABEL: Someone left that
for me at the front desk.

00:12.638 --> 00:13.931
It's Tim Kono's phone.

00:13.931 --> 00:14.932
- What?
- Whoa!

00:14.932 --> 00:16.350
- Tim thought he was gonna get murdered?

00:16.350 --> 00:19.269
- He'd been trying to take down this black
market jewelry dealer named Angel.

00:19.269 --> 00:20.979
CHARLES:
Say hello to Angel.

00:20.979 --> 00:22.105
- Teddy Dimas?

00:22.105 --> 00:24.858
- I'm writing you a check,
and it's gonna be large.

00:24.858 --> 00:28.111
CHARLES: That's right. Our prime sponsor
is now our prime suspect.

00:28.904 --> 00:30.405
MABEL:
Hey, where'd you get that?

00:30.822 --> 00:32.616
- Found it.
MABEL: Why was Tim after the ring

00:32.616 --> 00:35.577
that Zoe had the night she died?
OSCAR: No, she didn't have it.

00:35.577 --> 00:36.662
Not when she died.

00:36.662 --> 00:38.664
[muffled banging]

00:38.664 --> 00:40.457
♪

00:46.839 --> 00:49.633
♪ dramatic strings playing ♪

00:53.387 --> 00:55.806
MAN: What does it mean
to be a fan of something?

00:55.806 --> 00:57.307
[street noise]

00:57.307 --> 01:00.602
For me, it means undying absolute loyalty.

01:01.645 --> 01:04.230
Being a fan is like being married.

01:04.230 --> 01:07.234
You don't quit, no matter how bad it gets.

01:08.151 --> 01:10.863
That's how I feel about
the Only Murders podcast.

01:10.863 --> 01:13.991
- Can't believe it's been another
week without a new episode.

01:13.991 --> 01:17.244
- The fuck are they doing up there?
They just went silent.

01:17.244 --> 01:20.622
- Watch the language around Grant.
- What do I fuckin' care?

01:20.622 --> 01:23.125
- Guys, what if we see Bunny? [laughs]

01:23.125 --> 01:24.751
Or Howard the cat guy?

01:24.751 --> 01:26.253
Or Charles,

01:26.253 --> 01:29.214
Oliver, Mabel?
I don't know what I'd do.

01:29.631 --> 01:32.050
I don't wanna leave this spot
until they reveal

01:32.050 --> 01:33.677
who killed Tim Kono!

01:33.677 --> 01:36.722
- Calm down, Sam. Pass the holes.

01:36.722 --> 01:39.016
SAM:
We call ourselves the Arconiacs.

01:39.016 --> 01:42.603
We met on a message board:
The Itty-Bitty Omit-Bitty Committee,

01:42.603 --> 01:45.105
which I founded.
Ever since Fallon,

01:45.105 --> 01:47.649
OMITB has been having a moment,

01:47.649 --> 01:50.110
but we are the day-oners.

01:50.110 --> 01:52.237
Some fans are Mabelines.

01:52.237 --> 01:55.157
Some are Haden-Maidens.
A few, like me,

01:55.157 --> 01:58.243
are Putnuts. [laughs]
Oliver's my favorite.

01:58.243 --> 02:02.122
- I've been a member of six different
true crime podcast fan communities...

02:03.415 --> 02:06.835
but I have never had less faith in
a creative team than I do right now.

02:06.835 --> 02:08.920
- And what about that Sting cameo?

02:08.920 --> 02:11.131
Like Sting's gonna be the murderer.
[sighs]

02:11.131 --> 02:13.425
- A whole episode with no stakes.

02:13.425 --> 02:16.094
- Okay, guys,
why are you being so negative?

02:16.094 --> 02:18.347
Do you even like this podcast?

02:18.347 --> 02:19.848
- Love it!
- It's a revelation.

02:19.848 --> 02:22.142
- Well then, trust the team, okay?

02:22.142 --> 02:25.020
You want stakes?
You're gonna get stakes.

02:25.020 --> 02:26.772
They're probably right around the corner.

02:26.772 --> 02:29.775
♪ lively theme song playing ♪

02:29.775 --> 02:32.778
♪ vocalizing ♪

03:14.653 --> 03:18.073
[van rumbling, tires squealing]
[car honking]

03:19.449 --> 03:21.577
[panting, gasping]

03:21.577 --> 03:23.245
- What is that smell?

03:23.245 --> 03:24.830
- Jeez, I don't know. It-it...

03:24.830 --> 03:28.667
Smells like formaldehyde. You know,
they use that to preserve corpses.

03:28.667 --> 03:29.751
- Corpses?

03:30.586 --> 03:33.088
- [panting] Do you know

03:33.088 --> 03:36.508
that I was the first director to
use a real cadaver on stage?

03:36.508 --> 03:39.469
In Tuesdays At Bernie's.
It was my dual adaptation

03:39.469 --> 03:42.181
of Tuesdays With Morrie
and Weekend At Bernie's.

03:42.181 --> 03:43.182
- What?

03:43.182 --> 03:45.893
[brakes squeal]
[Mabel grunting]

03:45.893 --> 03:47.186
[door slams]

03:49.271 --> 03:51.023
- Theo, Theo, Theo.

03:51.023 --> 03:53.066
Listen to me. I-- Oh, I'm sorry.

03:53.066 --> 03:55.277
I know that was insensitive.
It's a touchy subject.

03:55.277 --> 03:56.570
I-- Ow!

03:57.446 --> 03:59.198
- Now, now, Theo.

03:59.198 --> 04:01.491
These are friends.

04:01.491 --> 04:03.076
[sighs] Apologies for my son.

04:03.076 --> 04:04.494
[Oliver gags]

04:04.494 --> 04:06.330
He hates the theater,
but he's very dramatic.

04:06.330 --> 04:08.790
- T-Teddy, this is all just

04:08.790 --> 04:11.001
a m-mis...
[gulls cawing]

04:11.001 --> 04:12.753
Why are we at a dump?

04:13.212 --> 04:16.005
- Are you gonna leave
these dead bodies here?

04:16.005 --> 04:17.757
[laughs]

04:17.757 --> 04:21.512
- I like you.
You ask interesting questions.

04:21.512 --> 04:23.013
Let me give you a lift home.

04:23.013 --> 04:26.016
♪

04:33.440 --> 04:34.525
I like this seat.

04:35.609 --> 04:38.654
Theo can't read my lips
or see me in the rear-view,

04:38.654 --> 04:40.155
which is nice.

04:40.155 --> 04:43.367
Because it's not good for a son to hear,

04:43.367 --> 04:47.120
or see, his father say certain things.

04:48.330 --> 04:52.292
For a long time,
I felt ashamed to have a deaf son.

04:52.292 --> 04:55.003
[sighs] It ended my marriage, actually.

04:56.171 --> 04:58.632
That and, you know,
all the whores.

04:58.632 --> 05:00.843
But then I grew to appreciate

05:00.843 --> 05:02.845
Theo's perspective.

05:02.845 --> 05:04.763
I learned ASL,

05:04.763 --> 05:08.183
which many parents of
deaf children do not do.

05:08.183 --> 05:09.268
Did you know that?

05:09.268 --> 05:11.603
- Is that right?
- Yeah, I've heard that.

05:11.603 --> 05:13.105
- I didn't know that.

05:13.105 --> 05:16.608
- Through Theo,
I realized the beauty of silence.

05:18.151 --> 05:21.280
It makes for beautiful
friendships and partnerships

05:21.280 --> 05:24.575
when those who may know
certain things about you

05:24.575 --> 05:27.828
can act as if they never
heard those things.

05:27.828 --> 05:31.039
- We hear you loud and clear, Teddy.

05:31.039 --> 05:34.334
Or we don't. I don-- I'm not exactly
sure what you're talking about.

05:34.334 --> 05:37.713
- I'm talking about what you've
heard and seen about me.

05:37.713 --> 05:40.424
My side jewelry interests.

05:40.424 --> 05:42.551
Which I admit is fascinating in a...

05:42.551 --> 05:45.304
ghoulish and psychologically
compelling way.

05:45.804 --> 05:49.683
A good subject for a podcast,
just not yours.

05:49.683 --> 05:52.102
Because your podcast needs to end.

05:53.020 --> 05:55.022
You can end it with dignity.

05:56.106 --> 05:57.858
Or you can end it posthumously.

05:57.858 --> 06:00.027
- We know what you did to Tim Kono.

06:00.027 --> 06:01.987
- We don't know shit about Tim Kono.

06:03.739 --> 06:06.116
That's why I feel at ease here.

06:06.116 --> 06:09.578
That, and I know Ollie would never
say bad things about someone

06:09.578 --> 06:12.497
who's been so good to him.
- No, no, no, no.

06:12.497 --> 06:14.875
- Here's what I'd like.

06:14.875 --> 06:18.128
To wake up tomorrow morning, say 7:00 AM,

06:18.128 --> 06:20.088
to find a final episode of the show

06:20.088 --> 06:22.132
I so generously fund,

06:22.132 --> 06:24.426
and hear that you are wrong.

06:24.426 --> 06:27.095
Sadly, Tim Kono shot himself,

06:27.095 --> 06:30.265
and, uh, the reason why is going to be...

06:31.058 --> 06:32.309
loneliness.

06:32.309 --> 06:34.061
♪

06:34.061 --> 06:36.104
Or some thinky shit like that.

06:36.563 --> 06:38.982
- It's definitely an area.
TEDDY: But make it good.

06:38.982 --> 06:41.235
You're the artists.

06:41.235 --> 06:43.237
I'm just a guy with some delis...

06:44.363 --> 06:47.574
who'd hate to see any more
bad things happen to the tenants

06:47.574 --> 06:49.076
in his building.

06:49.993 --> 06:52.079
You'll make the right choice.

06:52.079 --> 06:54.373
Because if you don't, well,

06:54.373 --> 06:55.582
I know where you live.

06:55.582 --> 06:58.168
♪

07:02.965 --> 07:05.342
- Hey. Careful.
- Go, go, go.

07:06.468 --> 07:08.387
- Hey! Uh, Oliver? Whoa.

07:08.387 --> 07:11.640
- Wait, are you Mabel?
- That's totally Mabel.

07:11.640 --> 07:13.767
- Oh my god, do we have fans?

07:13.767 --> 07:15.352
- Oh, thank god, we have fans!

07:15.352 --> 07:17.521
- Where's the new episode?
- Shouldn't you be recording?

07:17.521 --> 07:20.357
- Yeah, we don't work for you,
you vultures!

07:20.357 --> 07:22.484
- Okay. I'm so sorry. We're in a hurry.
- We believe in you.

07:24.278 --> 07:26.071
- I'm sorry, where did you get that?

07:26.071 --> 07:28.073
- Oh, homemade merch.

07:28.073 --> 07:29.491
Worked on it myself, so...

07:29.491 --> 07:32.160
- Out of curiosity, how much would
you pay for an official one?

07:32.160 --> 07:33.787
- Oh my god, Putnam, let's go!

07:33.787 --> 07:37.499
- [laughs] That was a classic
Oliver-Mabel exchange!

07:37.499 --> 07:40.502
Hey, we're dying for the next episode!
- We may be, too!

07:40.502 --> 07:42.754
[Sam laughing]
[knocking]

07:42.754 --> 07:44.506
- Open up! It's us!

07:44.506 --> 07:46.800
- You know, we really oughta have
a key in case he falls in the tub.

07:46.800 --> 07:48.260
He's not steady on his feet, you know.

07:48.260 --> 07:50.137
♪

07:50.137 --> 07:52.055
Charles!

07:52.055 --> 07:55.225
- [gasps] Oh hey, come in.
Charles is getting bagels.

07:58.604 --> 08:00.898
- [growls] Okay...

08:01.356 --> 08:03.859
MABEL:
So, uh, did you and Charles...

08:04.443 --> 08:07.362
How do I say this?
- Celebrate one another's bodies?

08:07.362 --> 08:08.572
- Oh, we went right there.

08:09.114 --> 08:10.657
- Oh Jesus...

08:10.657 --> 08:12.743
- Okay. Brazzos.

08:12.743 --> 08:14.286
- Brazzos was our safe word.

08:14.286 --> 08:17.080
- And what's the safe word for me
to get out of this conversation?

08:17.080 --> 08:19.374
- Are you guys okay?
Oh, do you want a Splenda?

08:19.374 --> 08:21.919
- Jan, please, we're focused
on staying alive here.

08:21.919 --> 08:25.130
- Okay, no Splenda. You know,
there's some not-so-great studies.

08:25.130 --> 08:29.009
- Hey! Hey, guys! Glad to
have you back! What a morning!

08:29.009 --> 08:31.887
- Sure is. We've had quite the time.

08:31.887 --> 08:34.389
We survived a truck full of corpses

08:34.389 --> 08:36.850
and an implicit death threat
from Teddy Dimas,

08:36.850 --> 08:38.477
but good thing you got bagels.

08:38.477 --> 08:41.020
- Well, actually,
I just got enough for Jan and me,

08:41.020 --> 08:42.731
but-- Wait, you know what?
That's not true

08:42.731 --> 08:44.900
because these blueberry bad boys

08:44.900 --> 08:47.611
are going right into the freez--

08:47.611 --> 08:48.904
Did you say "death threat"?

08:48.904 --> 08:51.240
- Uh-huh.
- Dimas threatened to kill us.

08:51.865 --> 08:53.700
- Are you alright?
OLIVER: Oh,

08:53.700 --> 08:55.827
Tim-Tom-riffic. But Teddy--

08:55.827 --> 08:58.872
and he never mentioned this to me,
you know how modest he can be--

08:58.872 --> 09:01.291
turns out, is a psychotic grave robber,

09:01.291 --> 09:03.126
who says that if we don't drop

09:03.126 --> 09:06.296
a final episode by morning,
saying that he did nothing,

09:06.296 --> 09:08.423
he's gonna drop a few
bullets in our skulls.

09:08.423 --> 09:10.467
JAN:
Teddy Dimas doesn't know what we know,

09:10.467 --> 09:13.095
and we know a lot more now.

09:13.095 --> 09:15.430
- Wait. What do we know?

09:15.430 --> 09:19.017
- Jan and I spent the morning
going through Tim Kono's phone,

09:19.017 --> 09:21.270
and we made a ton of secret discoveries.

09:21.270 --> 09:24.189
- Let's just say it sends
our investigation

09:24.189 --> 09:26.149
into a whole new direction.

09:26.149 --> 09:28.151
[Charles laughs]
- [quietly] Okay...

09:28.151 --> 09:29.194
- Isn't she a natural?

09:29.194 --> 09:30.946
[both groan]

09:30.946 --> 09:33.615
- Tim was a meticulous record keeper.

09:33.615 --> 09:35.868
There are notes and photos in here.

09:35.868 --> 09:38.871
There's scans of receipts
and newspaper clippings.

09:38.871 --> 09:42.040
So, putting them all together,
we found out

09:42.040 --> 09:44.626
why he was after the Dimases.

09:44.626 --> 09:46.587
He saw Teddy's son Theo

09:46.587 --> 09:49.882
push a girl from the roof here at
the Arconia almost 10 years ago.

09:50.924 --> 09:54.052
- It was Theo that Tim saw.

09:54.052 --> 09:56.597
- Teddy threatened Tim to keep him quiet,
but Tim was working

09:56.597 --> 09:59.808
to bring Teddy down till the day he died.
And then he stopped.

09:59.808 --> 10:01.727
- Yeah 'cause Teddy killed him!

10:01.727 --> 10:03.979
- Whoa, let's not leap to conclusions

10:03.979 --> 10:05.898
'cause I don't see that in this phone.

10:05.898 --> 10:08.358
- Okay, I can't. I can't do this.
- Um, Charlie?

10:08.358 --> 10:09.693
A word.
- Sure.

10:09.693 --> 10:11.820
- I'll set these up. We're sharing.
- Alright.

10:12.696 --> 10:16.283
Isn't she the best?
- Oh, totally. Amazing.

10:16.283 --> 10:18.911
J-just love her. So many opinions.
- Yes,

10:18.911 --> 10:21.455
we're very, very happy for you, okay? But,

10:21.455 --> 10:23.749
there's something that may have happened.

10:23.749 --> 10:26.627
- We... had sex. Together.

10:26.627 --> 10:30.506
- Ew, yes. Okay, I know that,
but shit just got super real,

10:30.506 --> 10:33.884
and if we want to take down
Dimas before 7:00 AM, first...

10:33.884 --> 10:34.968
Is that what we're gonna do?

10:36.220 --> 10:37.888
A nod or a "no," guys...

10:37.888 --> 10:39.306
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.
- [agreeing]

10:39.306 --> 10:42.768
- Then, we need real help.
We need real backup.

10:43.393 --> 10:46.772
- Who from?
- The person who gave us Tim's phone.

10:46.772 --> 10:49.775
♪

10:49.775 --> 10:51.944
[seagulls cawing]
[waves washing ashore]

10:51.944 --> 10:54.696
[taxi doors open, shut]

10:55.155 --> 10:56.698
- I'll handle this.

10:56.698 --> 10:58.784
I played this scene
a million times on Brazzos--

10:58.784 --> 11:00.285
- Oh, don't say that word.

11:01.745 --> 11:03.747
- How can I help you?

11:03.747 --> 11:05.207
[distant ship horn]

11:05.207 --> 11:07.459
- It's money time, baby.

11:07.459 --> 11:09.711
Payday's here,
and the check is in the mail.

11:09.711 --> 11:11.964
As in the deceased murdered male

11:11.964 --> 11:14.466
at the Arconia, Tim Kono.
That's right. I said murdered.

11:14.466 --> 11:17.094
- Okay, I heard murdered, but what
the fuck else was the rest of that?

11:17.094 --> 11:19.221
- Well, it's, uh, police talk,

11:19.221 --> 11:20.305
isn't it?
- No.

11:20.305 --> 11:24.101
- We are part of a concern

11:24.101 --> 11:27.396
that has reason to believe Tim Kono
was murdered by the Dimas family.

11:28.021 --> 11:30.774
- The deli people?
- Delis, but also crime.

11:30.774 --> 11:33.277
- Based on the evidence
we found on Tim's phone.

11:33.277 --> 11:35.112
- Uh-huh. And how did you get said phone?

11:35.612 --> 11:38.115
- Well, you gave--
- Sh, sh, sh, sh, sh...

11:38.115 --> 11:40.909
Maybe... whoever did that...

11:41.618 --> 11:45.080
still has some lingering
questions about Tim's death,

11:45.080 --> 11:47.249
and is up against enormous obstacles

11:47.249 --> 11:49.418
and was hoping you could
help them by releasing

11:49.418 --> 11:52.296
a podcast episode with all your evidence.

11:52.296 --> 11:53.755
- So, it was you.

11:54.590 --> 11:56.508
- I mean, if we make that episode--

11:56.508 --> 11:57.968
DETECTIVE WILLIAMS:
You don't want to be sitting ducks.

11:57.968 --> 12:00.429
I got you. I'm low-key running

12:00.429 --> 12:03.265
a tox report and fingerprint
scan off the laptop

12:03.265 --> 12:06.185
someone typed Kono's goodbye on.
The rest is on you.

12:06.185 --> 12:09.438
- Thank you so much.
And I am so, so sorry

12:09.438 --> 12:12.482
about the things that Charles and Mabel
said about you in episode one.

12:13.400 --> 12:16.028
And two. Some of three.

12:16.028 --> 12:19.406
- Okay... So, let's just make sure

12:19.406 --> 12:21.116
we keep this tight. Okay?

12:21.116 --> 12:24.536
Especially if you're accusing
the Deli King? Alright?

12:24.536 --> 12:28.081
So, get the who, the how,
the why, and the why now.

12:28.081 --> 12:29.708
- Get-get the what and the what?

12:29.708 --> 12:32.586
- See, why would you say what?
I never said what. There's no what.

12:32.586 --> 12:34.087
It's the who,

12:34.087 --> 12:35.964
the how, the why,

12:35.964 --> 12:38.467
and the why now. Alright?
Make the case.

12:38.467 --> 12:40.219
And make sure it's super fuckin' tight!

12:41.094 --> 12:43.096
- And we need to make it by morning.

12:43.805 --> 12:45.682
[seagulls cawing]
CHARLES: The who,

12:45.682 --> 12:47.267
and the...
MABEL: The-the who...

12:47.267 --> 12:48.977
OLIVER: The who, the what...
CHARLES: Not the what.

12:48.977 --> 12:50.771
OLIVER: No! The why! The why.
MABEL: How...

12:52.564 --> 12:55.651
OLIVER: Oh, I think the night
in the truck is starting to get to me.

12:55.651 --> 12:57.069
Is anyone hungry?

12:57.069 --> 13:00.697
I cannot function with all this
pressure and nothing to dip.

13:00.697 --> 13:03.242
CHARLES:
But what do we have for the why now?

13:03.242 --> 13:04.785
MABEL:
Nothing, really...

13:04.785 --> 13:05.827
[knocking]

13:09.164 --> 13:10.666
CHARLES: Oh!

13:15.712 --> 13:17.047
- Homemade pizza rolls.

13:17.047 --> 13:20.133
- [chuckles] Oh, that's great...

13:20.133 --> 13:22.928
- Well, I guess the mystery of what
we're gonna snack on is solved!

13:22.928 --> 13:25.138
[laughs] I want to show you this place.

13:26.390 --> 13:28.392
- No to this. No.

13:28.392 --> 13:30.185
- I totally agree. [sniffs]

13:30.185 --> 13:33.021
But, gotta admit, these pizza rolls
smell good. What do you think?

13:33.021 --> 13:35.107
- Stop.
[rhythmic knock]

13:35.107 --> 13:37.568
- Did someone order up a party?

13:37.568 --> 13:38.986
[sighs]

13:41.697 --> 13:44.616
Hey... Oscar. [growls]

13:45.325 --> 13:46.952
- Thanks for finally answering my texts.

13:46.952 --> 13:49.121
- Sorry. I've been a little preoccupied

13:49.121 --> 13:51.623
and minorly traumatized.
- Huh?

13:52.833 --> 13:54.501
I got big news about the case.

13:54.918 --> 13:57.045
Oh, what's that smell? I'm starving.

13:57.045 --> 13:59.798
- Nice to meet another member
of the team. Hi, I'm Jan.

13:59.798 --> 14:03.302
- Uh, Oscar. Those look amazing. [laughs]

14:03.302 --> 14:05.929
- And homemade!
I mean, how fun is this?

14:06.680 --> 14:08.640
We're becoming a community.

14:09.016 --> 14:12.269
OSCAR: Mm-hmm.
- So, what's the big news?

14:12.269 --> 14:15.731
- Oh, I met up with that Cutter guy.
- Oh, that's the jewelry connection.

14:15.731 --> 14:17.566
- The one Tim met up with
before he got iced.

14:17.566 --> 14:20.152
- Okay, so did you get the green ring?

14:20.152 --> 14:22.154
OSCAR:
No, that's the thing.

14:22.154 --> 14:23.655
Cutter sold it.

14:24.489 --> 14:25.532
To Kono.

14:26.450 --> 14:28.660
Tim actually got it the day
before he was killed.

14:28.660 --> 14:30.787
- Tim had Zoe's ring?

14:31.163 --> 14:33.081
- No, no. We didn't find it
in his apartment,

14:33.081 --> 14:35.959
and I have every piece
of jewelry he had in there.

14:35.959 --> 14:37.169
- Maybe whoever killed him took it.

14:38.795 --> 14:40.214
- The Dimases!
OLIVER: Yeah.

14:40.214 --> 14:41.965
- I mean, who else would
care about that ring?

14:41.965 --> 14:43.550
- That's direct evidence!

14:43.550 --> 14:46.678
- And that's our why now.
- Oh, is it though?

14:47.429 --> 14:49.223
I don't know. It...

14:49.223 --> 14:51.391
It's all circumstantial without the ring.

14:51.391 --> 14:53.519
We don't know the Dimases have it.

14:53.519 --> 14:55.103
[laughs] Circumstantial.

14:55.103 --> 14:57.064
Always wanted to throw that word around.

14:57.064 --> 14:58.857
[Charles and Jan laugh]

14:58.857 --> 15:02.361
Oh god, this is so exciting!
Thank you for inviting me into this.

15:02.361 --> 15:04.446
- [quietly] Although we didn't.
- I'm sorry?

15:04.446 --> 15:06.156
- Our pleasure. It's great.

15:06.156 --> 15:08.158
- And now, we need
to know how they did it.

15:08.158 --> 15:09.368
- If they did it.

15:10.869 --> 15:13.455
- Okay, you know what?
Guys, I need air

15:13.455 --> 15:17.251
and, uh, some dip for
these really dry rolls.

15:19.253 --> 15:21.713
- These will pair very nicely
with Gut Milk.

15:21.713 --> 15:23.131
♪

15:23.131 --> 15:24.675
[both laugh]

15:25.717 --> 15:28.637
[traffic noise]

15:28.637 --> 15:31.014
[bag crinkling]
[street chatter]

15:32.850 --> 15:35.853
[chatter gets louder]

15:35.853 --> 15:36.979
- Oh wait! Hey!

15:37.980 --> 15:40.691
- Jesus, don't you people
have a home to go to?

15:40.691 --> 15:43.151
What happened to the kid?
- Grant had a piano lesson.

15:43.151 --> 15:45.571
- Also, he got tired of
waiting for a new episode.

15:45.571 --> 15:47.573
Kids these days.

15:47.573 --> 15:50.200
Everything is binge, binge, binge.
- Yeah.

15:50.200 --> 15:53.579
- They'll never know the pleasure of
waiting for just a crumb of what you want.

15:54.830 --> 15:57.332
My daughter says I'm not
welcome at her wedding.

15:57.332 --> 15:59.251
- Well... Jesus...

15:59.251 --> 16:01.378
- Uh, but-but we know that

16:01.378 --> 16:03.338
you are on the cusp of something big,

16:03.338 --> 16:05.299
and I want to share in that cusp.

16:05.299 --> 16:08.010
- Exactly right.
The resolution is moments away.

16:08.010 --> 16:10.429
- It's not just one suspect, right?

16:10.429 --> 16:11.722
♪

16:11.722 --> 16:13.932
- Why do you think that?
- Logistics.

16:13.932 --> 16:16.185
And the timing with
the fire alarm that night.

16:16.935 --> 16:20.022
- Interesting. Well, it-it...
Anyway, it's all coming together.

16:20.022 --> 16:23.150
- It's amazing! I'm so buzzed!
- Ah, thank you.

16:23.150 --> 16:26.111
- I feel like Tim Kono the night
that he wrote those suicide notes!

16:26.111 --> 16:27.112
- Uh...

16:27.905 --> 16:28.906
Are you all busy right now?

16:28.906 --> 16:30.365
- No.
- Mm-mmm. No.

16:30.365 --> 16:31.825
- Come with me.

16:31.825 --> 16:34.077
- [excited squealing]

16:39.041 --> 16:41.084
- Reinforcements, kids!

16:41.084 --> 16:43.420
- Oh shit.
[fans giggling]

16:43.420 --> 16:45.881
- More people?
- What is happening right now?

16:45.881 --> 16:48.133
- Losing it. Totally losing it!

16:48.133 --> 16:50.302
[gasps] You're so pretty.

16:50.302 --> 16:51.929
- Oh, thank you.
- Mm?

16:51.929 --> 16:54.473
- Sam, Paulette, Marv, meet...

16:54.473 --> 16:56.391
Well, you know them.

16:56.391 --> 16:57.601
- You all...

16:57.601 --> 16:59.978
- Big fans of the podcast. You're Tie-Dye.

16:59.978 --> 17:01.188
[nervous laugh]

17:01.188 --> 17:02.856
- The OG! [giggling]

17:02.856 --> 17:05.442
- And I'm Jan. Introducing myself.

17:05.442 --> 17:06.318
- Oh.
- Hey.

17:06.318 --> 17:08.819
- Jan is my girlfriend.
- I am?

17:10.280 --> 17:11.740
- If you want to be.
- Yes.

17:11.740 --> 17:13.407
MARV:
What a handsome couple.

17:13.407 --> 17:14.952
My ex-wife was way younger, too.

17:16.203 --> 17:19.373
- Oh man, this is gonna break
Haden-Maiden hearts on the boards.

17:19.373 --> 17:21.375
[sighs]
- [laughs] What I'd give.

17:21.375 --> 17:24.502
- Okay, um, us three, we need to talk.

17:25.170 --> 17:26.755
Excuse me.
OLIVER: Okay. Yeah...

17:26.755 --> 17:29.758
[overlapping chatter]

17:33.679 --> 17:34.972
- Hey...
- Uh, hey.

17:35.514 --> 17:36.807
Ah...
[shutter snaps]

17:38.851 --> 17:42.104
- What are they doing here?
- We need help with the how.

17:42.104 --> 17:44.523
- From them?
- They know more than we do.

17:44.523 --> 17:46.483
Certainly more than Jan, who is...

17:46.483 --> 17:49.528
How do I put this politely?
Reverse-helpful.

17:50.445 --> 17:54.074
Like a French pig who can sense
truffles buried underground

17:54.074 --> 17:56.994
from miles away,
only the truffles are bad ideas.

17:56.994 --> 17:59.371
- That is my girlfriend
you're talking about,

17:59.371 --> 18:00.873
and we had sex.
I don't know if I said that.

18:00.873 --> 18:02.374
- Please stop talking about that.
- Guys,

18:02.374 --> 18:06.420
these fans listen to every episode,
over and over.

18:06.420 --> 18:08.881
They're us before we took this on.

18:08.881 --> 18:12.009
Wouldn't we want us on this case
before we were us?

18:12.926 --> 18:14.386
- Not a bad point.

18:14.386 --> 18:16.013
- Not a very clear point.

18:16.013 --> 18:19.308
- Look, do I wish our fans
were a little more hip? Yes.

18:19.308 --> 18:20.726
Do I wish they were

18:20.726 --> 18:23.812
a tad more on top of their hygiene?
Absolutely.

18:23.812 --> 18:26.023
Do they have a-a confused

18:26.023 --> 18:28.275
look in their eyes, like a dog
that's heard a strange sound?

18:28.275 --> 18:32.070
Yeah. But, strap that dog to a sled,

18:32.070 --> 18:33.614
and, baby,

18:33.614 --> 18:35.949
you'll be flying across the tundra.
[snorts]

18:37.868 --> 18:39.036
[disgusted sigh]

18:39.036 --> 18:41.788
♪

18:41.788 --> 18:43.957
- Tim Kono lives on the ninth floor,

18:43.957 --> 18:46.126
but on that night,

18:46.126 --> 18:47.753
he got on the elevator

18:47.753 --> 18:50.547
with a trash bag from floor six.

18:50.547 --> 18:52.132
Why?

18:52.716 --> 18:54.218
- How did we miss that?

18:55.886 --> 18:58.180
- Floor six is Teddy's floor.
PAULETTE: Cool,

18:58.180 --> 19:00.307
but was it Tim's garbage
or was it Teddy's?

19:00.766 --> 19:03.101
- It's a good question.
- And...

19:03.101 --> 19:05.521
did Teddy write those notes?

19:07.022 --> 19:09.399
Okay, as I said to Paula Abdul

19:09.399 --> 19:11.610
during our production of Hedda Gabler...
- Oi.

19:11.610 --> 19:13.862
- we gotta start thinking
outside the box here.

19:13.862 --> 19:16.490
- Guys, I know we all
like the Dimas stuff,

19:16.490 --> 19:18.909
but what about the cat?
- The who?

19:18.909 --> 19:20.869
- Well, I'm just going
over your notes here,

19:20.869 --> 19:23.372
and why aren't we looking
more at this man,

19:23.372 --> 19:25.624
Howard Morris?
- Okay...

19:25.624 --> 19:28.669
- Wait, you're suggesting
an entirely new suspect.

19:28.669 --> 19:31.713
- It is outside the box.
- A little too outside the box.

19:31.713 --> 19:34.258
- Yeah, I have an idea.
Why don't we shove it back into the box,

19:34.258 --> 19:36.468
and hope they don't notice
it when we return it.

19:36.468 --> 19:39.221
- It's not crazy.
We did look into him at one point,

19:39.221 --> 19:41.640
and I still have
his cat's leg somewhere--

19:41.640 --> 19:45.018
- I'm just saying he's your first suspect,
and he's not a bad one.

19:45.018 --> 19:46.603
[murmuring]
- Everyone, everyone, everyone.

19:46.603 --> 19:49.356
You know, I-I... In no way do
I want to appear pushy here,

19:49.356 --> 19:51.066
but please shut up.

19:52.150 --> 19:53.443
I think I've got this.

19:54.862 --> 19:57.865
The suicide notes that
Tim Kono had in the trash bag

19:57.865 --> 20:00.200
the night he died.
They weren't cries for help.

20:00.868 --> 20:01.869
They were death threats.

20:01.869 --> 20:03.412
- [gasps] Mind blown.
- No!

20:03.412 --> 20:05.747
- The Dimases were threatening him,

20:05.747 --> 20:08.292
promising to make his death
look like a suicide.

20:09.168 --> 20:11.295
Teddy threatened us
the same way this morning.

20:12.254 --> 20:14.423
- Keep going.
- Oh, I will. But first,

20:14.423 --> 20:16.884
I have to visualize.
I'm a visualizer.

20:16.884 --> 20:19.511
Marv, Marv, I need you to be Theo Dimas,

20:19.511 --> 20:21.722
the deaf son.
- O-okay.

20:21.722 --> 20:23.891
- No, no. Don't, don't [laughs]

20:23.891 --> 20:25.684
ever do that again.

20:25.684 --> 20:28.478
Paulette, you are the doorman, Lester.

20:28.478 --> 20:30.647
- Psych.
- Okay.

20:30.647 --> 20:33.275
And you, Sam,

20:33.275 --> 20:35.360
you're Tim Kono.
[excited laugh]

20:35.360 --> 20:36.612
♪

20:36.612 --> 20:39.198
Dead! [laughs] But literally.

20:39.198 --> 20:40.616
He is dead.

20:41.200 --> 20:42.492
- Flashback!

20:42.492 --> 20:44.494
The day of the murder.

20:44.494 --> 20:46.788
Tim Kono enters the Arconia.

20:46.788 --> 20:48.707
And... action!

20:49.333 --> 20:51.585
- [awkwardly] Hello, Lester.

20:51.585 --> 20:54.463
What a normal afternoon
OLIVER: No, no, pointier.

20:54.463 --> 20:56.673
He has a very pointy delivery.
Isn't that right, Mabel?

20:56.673 --> 20:59.051
- Pointy?
- Well [stammers] just try it.

21:00.344 --> 21:02.387
- [pointedly] Hello, Lester.
Did I happen to receive

21:02.387 --> 21:04.681
a package with a ring in it?

21:04.681 --> 21:06.308
- No, not today, Mr. Kono.
[snaps]

21:06.308 --> 21:08.810
- Okay, so Tim enters his apartment,

21:08.810 --> 21:10.729
and then fire alarm. Whoop!

21:10.729 --> 21:13.106
Whoop! Whoop!

21:13.106 --> 21:16.318
So then, he opens his door, and Theo Dimas

21:16.318 --> 21:18.654
pushes his way in.
[grunts]

21:18.654 --> 21:19.905
No, no, no. Too-too rough.

21:19.905 --> 21:21.657
Too rough, Marv.
- But, I'm a killer.

21:21.657 --> 21:24.243
- We're just marking, Marv!

21:24.243 --> 21:25.827
Cuckoo! Cuckoo!

21:26.328 --> 21:27.829
Okay. They fight.

21:27.829 --> 21:29.331
♪

21:29.331 --> 21:31.458
Theo wants to protect
his dad from Tim exposing

21:31.458 --> 21:34.127
all his father's crimes.
He punches him in the stomach.

21:34.127 --> 21:35.295
[exaggerated grunt]

21:35.295 --> 21:38.173
Same way that, you know,
I was punched in the stomach at the dump.

21:38.173 --> 21:41.093
[gasping] Tim gasps for air.

21:41.093 --> 21:43.720
[loud gasp]
And then a pistol goes in his mouth.

21:43.720 --> 21:44.972
[groans]

21:46.223 --> 21:47.307
[grunt]

21:48.267 --> 21:50.394
[dramatic sigh]

21:50.394 --> 21:51.019
[grunt]

21:52.437 --> 21:53.897
We'll work on that.

21:53.897 --> 21:55.440
And finally,

21:55.440 --> 21:58.360
remember what Detective Williams
said about the fingerprints?

21:58.360 --> 22:00.654
Theo types the suicide message.

22:01.947 --> 22:04.283
And that's how it all went down.
What do you think?

22:06.410 --> 22:07.911
- Kind of a confusing theory.

22:07.911 --> 22:10.747
- Oh please, you're in a love daze.
It's air-tight.

22:10.747 --> 22:13.750
- And it's the how,
so we have to get the recording equipment.

22:13.750 --> 22:16.879
- I don't know, you guys. Don't you
think it feels a little too easy?

22:17.671 --> 22:19.756
I mean, I'd take another look at Howard.

22:19.756 --> 22:22.676
- Tim did not die because of a cat, Jan.

22:22.676 --> 22:24.469
He died because of jewels,

22:24.469 --> 22:28.140
and a ring, and if we're gonna do this,
we're gonna do it now or never.

22:28.140 --> 22:31.560
- It's 5:30 in the morning,
and we all know how you need a few takes

22:31.560 --> 22:33.145
before you're warmed up.

22:33.145 --> 22:34.605
[sighs]

22:34.605 --> 22:38.192
- Uh, Jan, we kinda worked
on this as a team together.

22:38.192 --> 22:40.402
- And I'm not on the team.

22:40.402 --> 22:42.112
- Well, I wouldn't put it like that.

22:42.112 --> 22:44.698
- Oh, I would because
your input is destructive,

22:44.698 --> 22:46.867
and your pizza rolls are chewy.

22:46.867 --> 22:49.745
Now, normally, I could forgive
one of those things, but not both.

22:49.745 --> 22:52.664
- You ate six of those pizza rolls,
and they're starting to show.

22:52.664 --> 22:56.084
- I beg of you. Please, exit.

22:56.710 --> 22:58.879
- Oh, I'll exit.
- No, no,

22:58.879 --> 23:00.047
you have great ideas--

23:00.047 --> 23:02.007
- Charles, let her go. We're on the clock.
[door opens]

23:02.007 --> 23:04.134
- Ja-- I think she's mad at me.
[door shuts]

23:04.134 --> 23:05.886
- Oh, she's definitely mad at you.

23:05.886 --> 23:08.263
- Okay, we need to
start recording this now.

23:08.263 --> 23:10.224
- Sam, any time, you can get up.

23:10.224 --> 23:12.142
- Are we sure-sure about this?

23:12.142 --> 23:14.186
We've taken a lot of
money from Teddy Dimas.

23:14.186 --> 23:16.104
I just wanna be sure-sure-sure.

23:16.104 --> 23:17.105
[elevator dings]

23:19.066 --> 23:20.859
[sighs]
[elevator doors shut]

23:22.194 --> 23:25.197
♪

23:33.789 --> 23:35.791
[keys jingling, unlocks door]

23:40.629 --> 23:43.841
♪

23:43.841 --> 23:46.301
CHARLES:
And that concludes the final episode of

23:46.301 --> 23:48.887
Only Murders In The Building.

23:48.887 --> 23:52.558
We'll be back in the unlikely event
another neighbor is murdered

23:52.558 --> 23:56.311
or we move to a more dangerous area.

23:56.311 --> 23:59.398
I'm your host, Charles-Haden Savage.

24:01.066 --> 24:02.025
[click]

24:02.776 --> 24:04.027
- There it is. We're done.

24:04.027 --> 24:06.572
OLIVER: Oh...
[applause]

24:07.197 --> 24:08.740
Did you really like it!?

24:08.740 --> 24:10.784
- I feel like I just watched
Prince record Purple Rain.

24:10.784 --> 24:13.871
- You really did it.
- Down comes the Deli King.

24:13.871 --> 24:16.874
- Make sure your friends listen.
Go spread the word.

24:16.874 --> 24:18.208
- Yes.

24:18.208 --> 24:21.211
- And find some other interests.

24:21.211 --> 24:22.880
It's a big wide world out there.

24:23.547 --> 24:26.592
- Congratulations. We love you guys.
MABEL: Thank you.

24:26.592 --> 24:27.885
- Oh, love you. Love you.

24:27.885 --> 24:29.970
- Would love to talk merch.
OLIVER: No, no.

24:29.970 --> 24:31.305
- I actually do have a job.

24:31.305 --> 24:34.391
- I don't believe that.
- Thanks for being super fans.

24:34.391 --> 24:37.102
- Okay, before we send this...
[door shuts]

24:37.102 --> 24:39.605
we need to show somebody a sneak preview.

24:43.567 --> 24:47.279
CHARLES [on podcast]: Tim Kono had
stumbled upon Teddy Dimas' side business

24:47.279 --> 24:50.574
of grave robbing jewels from the dead.

24:50.574 --> 24:52.284
- No shit.

24:52.284 --> 24:55.287
[text notification chimes]
[sigh, soft laugh]

24:55.829 --> 24:57.706
[puts down paper, cup]

24:57.706 --> 25:00.709
♪

25:01.376 --> 25:03.420
[sighs] Goddammit.

25:13.472 --> 25:15.474
[knocking]

25:22.731 --> 25:24.942
CHARLES [on podcast]:
And the day Tim was murdered was the day

25:24.942 --> 25:28.445
he finally got the evidence that
backed up his story of what he saw

25:28.445 --> 25:31.657
the night his friend Zoe died.

25:31.657 --> 25:33.492
[on headphones]
Tim returned to the Arconia that day

25:33.492 --> 25:37.037
to be greeted by an ominous
warning waiting under his door.

25:37.037 --> 25:39.289
A suicide note.

25:39.289 --> 25:41.458
So, he stuffed the note in a trash bag

25:41.458 --> 25:43.377
and took the elevator down to six.

25:43.377 --> 25:47.172
[on speaker] He confronted Teddy
with the trash bag at Teddy's doorstep,

25:47.172 --> 25:50.717
then flashed a gun he recently
bought on the black market.

25:50.717 --> 25:53.804
The gun that would
become the murder weapon.

25:53.804 --> 25:57.224
Teddy pulls the fire alarm,
lingers outside Tim's apartment.

25:57.224 --> 26:01.019
When Tim tries to leave, Theo stuns
him with a punch to the stomach.

26:01.019 --> 26:03.146
The alarm covers the gunshot,

26:03.146 --> 26:05.774
Dimases make sure to
blend in with the residents

26:05.774 --> 26:08.861
walking downstairs during the fire alarm.

26:08.861 --> 26:12.364
CHARLES/SAM: Confident
they had gotten away with murder.

26:15.742 --> 26:17.160
- Something's bothering me.

26:17.160 --> 26:19.955
Why would the Dimases sponsor a podcast

26:19.955 --> 26:21.790
they knew might out them?

26:21.790 --> 26:23.333
- Hubris, I guess.

26:23.333 --> 26:25.335
- Everybody always blames hubris.

26:25.335 --> 26:28.338
You really buy that?
- Sometimes the truth is weird, okay?

26:30.674 --> 26:34.178
SAM: Real life doesn't always
resolve like mysteries do.

26:34.178 --> 26:35.304
[clink]
ALL: Cheers!

26:35.304 --> 26:37.055
- God bless us. Oh, no.

26:37.681 --> 26:39.266
Mm!

26:39.266 --> 26:42.394
You know, I'm gonna
miss this case a little...

26:42.394 --> 26:44.897
MABEL: Me, too.
[chatter fades out]

26:44.897 --> 26:46.315
[text chimes]

26:46.315 --> 26:49.318
♪

26:53.113 --> 26:54.406
[text chimes]

26:59.203 --> 27:00.662
[text chimes]

27:10.380 --> 27:12.132
- I know how you feel about Tim,

27:12.132 --> 27:14.259
but I did find this.

27:15.636 --> 27:17.679
- I can't reverse time,

27:17.679 --> 27:20.849
but I've been gathering all the jewels
and evidence I can find

27:20.849 --> 27:23.393
to prove the crimes of Teddy Dimas.

27:23.393 --> 27:25.562
I even have a lead on the emerald ring

27:25.562 --> 27:28.315
that can prove what I saw
the night Zoe died.

27:29.149 --> 27:31.568
It's all I can do to try to make up
for what happened,

27:32.736 --> 27:35.948
and for Oscar Torres,

27:35.948 --> 27:37.866
who was like a brother to me,

27:37.866 --> 27:39.868
to begin to say I'm sorry.

27:41.787 --> 27:44.873
Even though I can't forgive
myself for my silence,

27:44.873 --> 27:46.959
and for all he lost

27:46.959 --> 27:49.294
so unfairly,

27:49.294 --> 27:51.296
starting on that New Year's Eve.

27:52.089 --> 27:55.050
SAM:
And while some clues are important,

27:55.050 --> 27:57.052
some lead nowhere.

27:58.262 --> 28:01.139
- Yeah, man, as soon as the chief
saw "Dimases did it" trending,

28:01.139 --> 28:02.808
he told me to pick him up.

28:02.808 --> 28:06.186
[on phone]: Can you believe that this
is how crimes are solved now?

28:06.186 --> 28:08.105
- [laughs] I know. Isn't it fantastic?

28:08.105 --> 28:11.024
- And I'm genuinely impressed.
You nailed them.

28:11.024 --> 28:12.693
Fully nailed them.

28:12.693 --> 28:15.904
Teddy Dimas is in a world of
trouble for the Cassidy death,

28:15.904 --> 28:18.699
